Analysis of population and immigration in Catalonia.¶

Manel Lopez Melia.

The aim of this project is to study the relation between the shape of the population pyramids and the immigration rate of different Catalan cities.

All datasets in this work can be downloaded at https://www.idescat.cat/serveis/consultes/.

The packages that will be used are:

In [1]:
%matplotlib inline
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy.optimize import curve_fit

First let's print the first lines of the first dataset: population of each town in one year bins.

In [2]:
!head 'p2018_municipis_any_any.csv'

The first three lines can be omitted (skiprows=3) and the 'Any' (year) and 'Codi' (code) columns can be dropped too (usecols=columns). Notice that the separation is not ',', but ';'. Also, the separator for thousands is '.'.

As there are accents and other special characters in this dataset, encoding 'latin1' is used to read it.

Finally, the columns 'Municipi' (town) and 'Edats' (ages) are set as indices and the values of the rest of columns are changed from string type to float.

In [3]:

population_1yr = population_1yr.set_index(indices)

population_1yr[['Homes', 'Dones', 'Total']] = population_1yr[['Homes', 'Dones', 'Total']].apply(pd.to_numeric)

Example: population of Olot (2018).¶

A subset of the whole dataset can be taken: the population of the city of Olot. As can be seen in the !head command executed above, there are spaces before the town and ages labels, so the index to use is ' Olot', not 'Olot'.

The last row of each town subset is the total of each column. For this example, this row is omitted.

Also, instead of the indices of ages, a set of numeric indices can be set.

In [11]:
population_1yr_olot = population_1yr.loc[' Olot', :]
population_1yr_olot = population_1yr_olot.loc[' De 0 anys':' De 100 anys i més']

index = pd.Index([i for i in range(101)])
population_1yr_olot = population_1yr_olot.set_index(index)

In the graph above it can be seen how the men population is slightly greater than women's for ages up to 40 years, as commented, although the percentages are practically 50% for men and women. On the other hand, above 60 years the predominance of women is clear, reaching more than 70% for ages above 90 years.

The explanation for this "fall" in the graph could be because of women's higher life expectancy.

This graph can be repeated in binary: a bar is blue if there's more men than women and red else.

Like in previous graphs, it can be seen how the population pyramid is practically symmetric for ages below 40 years, meaning that there are as much men than women in each bin, and for ages greater than 60 years the population of men decreases more than women's, especially in the interval of 80 to 90 years.

Concerning the shape of this population pyramid, and that of some of the previous graphs, the explanation for its large width in the interval of ages from 40 to 60 years corresponds to the so-called baby-boom generation. Indeed, the increase of birth rate in Spain was approximately from the 60s to the 80s.

In all these graphs the difference between bins is sometimes great, making them look irregular in some occasions. This is, of course, due to the fact that the data is in bins of 1 year only. By changing to bins of 5 years, these irregularities will be smoothed and there will be less noise.

Relation between shape of population pyramids and immigration rates¶

Now that the dataframes have been studied with the example of Olot city, a more deep analysis can be done. The objective is to find a relation between the shape of the population pyramid and the immigration rate of Catalan cities.

First, notice that the "shape" of a population pyramid can be numerically described by its own bins scaled with respect to the total population of that town. The immigration rate will be scaled to this total too, so the percentages are comparable.

The men and women columns of population_total are not needed here:

In [91]:
total = population_total['Total']

The dependent variable x is created: it contains the population born abroad of each town in Catalonia. The rows men and women are again dropped. It is then scaled to the total population of each town:

In [182]:
x = population_pob['Estranger'].drop([' Homes', ' Dones'], level=1)
x = x.reset_index().drop('Sexe', axis=1).set_index('Municipi')
x = x['Estranger']
x = x.div(total, axis=0)

See how it looks like:

Everything is ready now for curve fitting. The hypothesis is that the percentage of population in each bin is linearly dependent to the percentage of people born abroad in any town, so the function to fit is a line:

In [64]:
def f(x, a, b):
    return a + b * x

The following loop fits the data of each bin in ys to x and fills the lists of parameters that will be discussed later. It also plots the linear fits.

In [156]:
a_list = []
b_list = []
aunc_list = []
bunc_list = []
rsq_list = []

i = 0

for b in bin_list: 
    y = ys[:, b]
    popt, pcov = curve_fit(f, x, y)
    punc = np.sqrt(np.diag(pcov))
    rsq = 1 - ((y - f(x, *popt))**2).sum() / ((y - y.mean(axis=0))**2).sum()
    
    a_list.append(popt[0])
    b_list.append(popt[1])
    aunc_list.append(punc[0])
    bunc_list.append(punc[1])
    rsq_list.append(rsq)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(7, 7))
    
    plt.title('(' + str(i+1) + '/21) Linear fit. Bin: ' + bin_list_eng[i] + ' years')
    plt.xlabel('Immigration percentage')
    plt.ylabel('Population percentage, ' + bin_list_eng[i] + ' years')
    
    plt.ylim(-0.01, 0.14)
    
    plt.scatter(x, y, color='blue', s=1, label='Linear fit')
    plt.plot(x, f(x, *popt), color='red', label='Data')
    
    plt.text(0.35, 0.115, 'b = {:.3f} +/- {:.3f}'.format(popt[1], punc[1]))
    plt.text(0.35, 0.110, 'r^2 = {:.3f}'.format(rsq))
    
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid()
    plt.show()
    
    i += 1

The coefficient of determination $r^2$ is in all cases smaller than 0.1, which indicates a very bad fit. However, this is human science, and humans are not pure science, hence the huge dispersion of data in the above graphs is not surprising. In fact, for human science a coefficient $r^2 > 0.1$ is accepted as a good enough fit. In this case the highest $r^2$ value is

In [157]:
max(rsq_list)
Out[157]:
0.07747746300215574

It would be much nicer to have better values for $r^2$ so stronger conclusions could be made. Anyway, let's take a look at the values of the slopes:

In [169]:
plt.figure(figsize=(7, 7))

plt.title('Slopes of linear fits')
plt.xlabel('Years')
plt.ylabel('Slope b')

plt.scatter(bin_list_eng, b_list, color='red', s=30, marker='*', zorder=3)
plt.axhline(0, color='black', linestyle='--', linewidth=1)

plt.xticks(rotation=90)

plt.grid(zorder=0)
plt.show()

For ages up to 50 years, it looks like the population rate and the immigration rate are related with a positive slope. On the other hand, for ages greater than 50 years, this slope is negative. This means (very weakly because of the small $r^2$ values) that the higher the immigration rate of a town, the higher young people percentages and the lower old people percentages.

for b in bin_list: 
    y = ys[:, b][mask1]
    popt, pcov = curve_fit(f, x, y)
    punc = np.sqrt(np.diag(pcov))
    rsq = 1 - ((y - f(x, *popt))**2).sum() / ((y - y.mean(axis=0))**2).sum()
